  ## 6. Pros & Cons

  ### Pros

  * **Exceptional spin generation at low-to-medium effort.** The soft sponge and elite topsheet combine to make loop openings, serves, and short game feel almost effortlessly spinny. Players stepping down from harder rubbers will immediately feel more confident in their
   brushing game.
  * **Outstanding short game and touch.** Drops shots, short pushes, and all touch-based techniques are dramatically easier than on T05 or Dignics. This makes the FX a weapon for players whose game revolves around controlling the first few balls of the rally.
  * **Lower fatigue and effort threshold.** Because the rubber responds well to moderate input, players do not need to exert maximum effort to achieve high-quality shots. This makes it excellent for long matches, older players, or those with technique-first
  philosophies.
  * **Excellent consistency and error reduction.** The forgiving nature and high arc reduce unforced errors, particularly on opening loops and rally continuations.

  ### Cons

  * **Limited top-end power.** The soft sponge hits a ceiling on full-power shots. Kill loops, smashes, and flat hits lack the penetrating speed and snap of T05 or Dignics. Against hard-blocking or long-distance opponents, the FX can feel underpowered.
  * **Passive blocks can sit up.** The higher throw angle means that passive blocks against heavy topspin sometimes pop up rather than staying low. This can give aggressive opponents easy put-away opportunities.
  * **Spin sensitivity on receive.** The grippy topsheet and soft sponge make the FX fairly reactive to incoming spin. Players with less-developed reading skills may struggle with unexpected kick-offs, especially on BH blocks against heavy loops.
  * **Premium price.** As a Butterfly Tenergy product, the FX carries a premium price tag (typically $55–70 USD depending on market). The performance-per-dollar is good, but budget-conscious players have increasingly capable alternatives.

